-- Seoul shares fall in first response to Fed stimulus cut, China surveys
-- By Jungmin Jang
-- Mon Feb 03, 2014 01:14AM EST
-- None



SEOUL, Feb 3 (Reuters) - Seoul shares fell on Monday in their first response to developments during the market's long holiday closure, including a further cut in stimulus by the U.S. Federal Reserve and soft Chinese economic surveys.

The Korea Composite Stock Price Index (KOSPI) <.KS11> closed down 1.1 percent at 1,919.96 points. The market was closed on Thursday and Friday for Lunar New Year. Offshore investors on Monday sold a net 418.7 billion won ($391.2 million) of KOSPI shares, weighing on the main board. Turnover was lower than usual at 3.903 trillion Korean won compared to a five-day average of 4.224 trillion won, while decliners beat advancers by about 2 to 1.